2 (a) In this section, “Fund” means the Opioid Restitution Fund.
3 (b) There is an Opioid Restitution Fund.
4 (c) The purpose of the Fund is to retain the amount of settlement revenues
5 deposited to the Fund in accordance with subsection (e)(1) of this section.
6 (d) (1) The Fund is a special, nonlapsing fund that is not subject to § 7–302 of
7 this subtitle.
8 (2) The State Treasurer shall hold the Fund separately, and the
9 Comptroller shall account for the Fund.
10 (e) The Fund consists of:
11 (1) all revenues received by the State from any source resulting, directly or
12 indirectly, from any judgment against, or settlement with, opioid manufacturers, opioid
13 research associations, or any other person in the opioid industry relating to any claims
14 made or prosecuted by the State to recover damages for violations of State law; and
15 (2) the interest earnings of the Fund.
16 (f) The Fund may be used only to provide funds for THE PURPOSES SPECIFIED
17 IN SETTLEMENT AGREEMENTS AND JUDGMENTS RELATING TO CLAIMS BY THE
18 STATE AGAINST OPIOID MANUFACTURERS, OPIOID RESEARCH ASSOCIATIONS, OR
19 ANY OTHER PERSON IN THE OPIOID INDUSTRY FOR VIOLATIONS OF STATE LAW,
20 INCLUDING:
21 (1) programs, services, supports, and resources for evidence–based
22 substance use disorder prevention, treatment, recovery, or harm reduction that have the
23 purpose of:;
24 (i) improving access to medications proven to prevent or reverse an
25 overdose, including by supporting the initiative to co–locate naloxone with automated
26 external defibrillators placed in public buildings under § 13–518 of the Education Article;
27 (ii) supporting peer support specialists and screening, brief
28 intervention, and referral to treatment services for hospitals, correctional facilities, and
29 other high–risk populations;
30 (iii) increasing access to medications that support recovery from
31 substance use disorders; AND

